  <h2>The Spectrum of Scope</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Visual check.</strong> A look at an accessible, already-open tank and the readily visible
      parts of the system. It's quick and low-cost, but limited — it can miss anything not visible on
      the surface.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Locating and opening.</strong> Finding the tank (if its location isn't known) and
      opening the lids so the interior can actually be seen — a meaningful step up in what can be
      assessed.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Functional evaluation.</strong> A fuller inspection that may include pumping and flow or
      dye testing to see how the system handles real use, plus a closer look at the tank's components
      and, where possible, signs of how the drain field is performing.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Documentation.</strong> A written record of what was found — which is what makes an
      inspection useful in a transaction or as a baseline for the future.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Why Pumping Is Sometimes Part of It</h2>
  <p>
    A thorough inspection sometimes includes pumping the tank, and there's a good reason: with the tank
    emptied, the inspector can clearly see the interior walls, the baffles, and the true condition of
    things that are hidden when the tank is full. It also confirms the tank actually empties and
    refills as it should. Because pumping adds both thoroughness and cost, whether it's included is one
    of the clearest things to confirm when comparing inspections.
  </p>

  <h2>Matching the Inspection to the Purpose</h2>
  <p>
    The right level depends on why you're inspecting. A real-estate purchase usually justifies a more
    thorough, documented inspection, because a major decision rests on it — our guide on
    <a href="/septic-inspections-when-buying-a-home/">inspections when buying a home</a> explains why.
    A routine owner's check, or a look driven by a specific symptom, might be lighter. If you're not
    sure, describe the situation and let the provider recommend the scope.
  </p>

  <h2>Compare Scope, Not Just Price</h2>
  <p>
    The practical takeaway is simple: before comparing two inspection quotes, ask what each one
    actually includes — visual only, or locating, opening, testing, and documentation? A lower price
    for a lighter service isn't really cheaper if it doesn't answer the question you need answered. To
    arrange an inspection at the right depth, see
    <a href="/septic-inspection-cookeville-tn/">septic inspections</a> or
    <a href="/request-service/">request septic service</a> and describe the purpose.
  </p>
